WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.00 --> 00:00:02.94
For more on the Ukraine and Russian conflict,

00:00:02.94 --> 00:00:04.44
let's bring in Timothy Frye.

00:00:04.44 --> 00:00:06.36
He's the Marshall D. Shulman Professor

00:00:06.36 --> 00:00:09.27
of Post-Soviet Politics at Columbia University.

00:00:09.27 --> 00:00:11.79
Timothy is also the author of Weak Strongman--

00:00:11.79 --> 00:00:15.90
The Limits of Power in Putin's Russia.

00:00:15.90 --> 00:00:19.95
Timothy, I want to play some of what President Biden said today

00:00:19.95 --> 00:00:22.41
about the crisis in Ukraine and then come back to you.

00:00:22.41 --> 00:00:26.20


00:00:26.20 --> 00:00:28.95
The Russian Defense Minister reported today

00:00:28.95 --> 00:00:31.86
that some military units are leaving their positions

00:00:31.86 --> 00:00:33.81
near Ukraine.

00:00:33.81 --> 00:00:38.30
That would be good, but we have not yet verified that.

00:00:38.30 --> 00:00:42.38
Indeed, our analysts indicate that they remain very much

00:00:42.38 --> 00:00:44.82
in a threatening position.

00:00:44.82 --> 00:00:46.98
Not yet verified.

00:00:46.98 --> 00:00:49.35
Timothy, first of all, thank you for joining us.

00:00:49.35 --> 00:00:53.49
Now, tell me what would it mean if, in fact, Russia

00:00:53.49 --> 00:00:56.84
would begin a troop withdrawal.

00:00:56.84 --> 00:01:00.17
Well, the signals coming from Moscow are quite mixed.

00:01:00.17 --> 00:01:02.30
On the one hand, there's been an announcement

00:01:02.30 --> 00:01:05.06
that some troops from the South and the East

00:01:05.06 --> 00:01:10.61
are withdrawing back to base that has not been verified.

00:01:10.61 --> 00:01:14.78
At the same time, Russia still maintains the capacity

00:01:14.78 --> 00:01:18.95
to inflict great military damage on Ukraine

00:01:18.95 --> 00:01:22.67
both on its northern flank and on its Eastern flank regardless

00:01:22.67 --> 00:01:24.96
of whether or not those troops have been removed.

00:01:24.96 --> 00:01:26.85
So it's a very good sign.

00:01:26.85 --> 00:01:30.38
And it's also a good sign that the two sides

00:01:30.38 --> 00:01:33.83
continue to talk because each day without fighting

00:01:33.83 --> 00:01:36.14
is a good day.

00:01:36.14 --> 00:01:36.71
That's right.

00:01:36.71 --> 00:01:39.29
I mean, I understand that Russian President Vladimir

00:01:39.29 --> 00:01:42.57
Putin met with Germany's new chancellor, Olaf Scholz,

00:01:42.57 --> 00:01:44.10
on Tuesday, today.

00:01:44.10 --> 00:01:46.97
What is potentially at stake between these two countries

00:01:46.97 --> 00:01:48.44
if Ukraine is attacked?

00:01:48.44 --> 00:01:51.65
As you said, any day that there is no fighting is a good day.

00:01:51.65 --> 00:01:54.02
But of course, every day we kind of feel that pressure.

00:01:54.02 --> 00:01:55.37
We're not the only country.

00:01:55.37 --> 00:01:58.07
What would it mean to Russia-German relations?

00:01:58.07 --> 00:02:00.95
And how is that different from relations

00:02:00.95 --> 00:02:02.12
between Russia and the US?

00:02:02.12 --> 00:02:04.43
So it was important that Olaf Scholz, the chancellor

00:02:04.43 --> 00:02:07.94
of Germany, was in Moscow today meeting with President Putin

00:02:07.94 --> 00:02:11.21
to show that diplomacy continues.

00:02:11.21 --> 00:02:16.28
On the German side, the chancellor

00:02:16.28 --> 00:02:21.71
said that he would continue to pressure Ukraine in order

00:02:21.71 --> 00:02:25.97
to reach a compromise agreement with Russia known as Minsk II.

00:02:25.97 --> 00:02:29.06
This is an agreement that's not very favorable to Ukraine.

00:02:29.06 --> 00:02:32.27
But it is the only offer that's on the table and something

00:02:32.27 --> 00:02:34.97
that Moscow has pushed.

00:02:34.97 --> 00:02:37.91
At the same time, he also put some pressure

00:02:37.91 --> 00:02:39.74
on President Putin.

00:02:39.74 --> 00:02:42.83
Earlier in the day, the Russian parliament

00:02:42.83 --> 00:02:47.42
had voted to recognize the two regions in Ukraine

00:02:47.42 --> 00:02:49.88
where much of the fighting has taken place.

00:02:49.88 --> 00:02:53.72
And he warned President Putin that should that effort

00:02:53.72 --> 00:02:59.03
go forward that this would end any negotiations over the peace

00:02:59.03 --> 00:03:00.65
agreement in Ukraine.

00:03:00.65 --> 00:03:05.72
So again, both sides are trying to bargain.

00:03:05.72 --> 00:03:09.26
And part of the bargain is the public debate

00:03:09.26 --> 00:03:12.83
that is taking place as each side tries

00:03:12.83 --> 00:03:16.76
to sway public opinion in Ukraine and Russia, Europe,

00:03:16.76 --> 00:03:18.74
and the United States.

00:03:18.74 --> 00:03:21.05
And when you say each side, we're thinking US.

00:03:21.05 --> 00:03:22.01
We're thinking Germany.

00:03:22.01 --> 00:03:24.05
But let's focus on NATO.

00:03:24.05 --> 00:03:25.94
I understand, of course, that Ukraine is not

00:03:25.94 --> 00:03:27.54
a member of NATO.

00:03:27.54 --> 00:03:30.74
Neither will it be according to pretty much every expert

00:03:30.74 --> 00:03:33.41
out there and President Biden and NATO members.

00:03:33.41 --> 00:03:35.78
Now, how would--

00:03:35.78 --> 00:03:36.81
I understand that.

00:03:36.81 --> 00:03:41.06
However, Ukraine is getting a lot of help from NATO members.

00:03:41.06 --> 00:03:45.68
What would it look like if there was an intervention by Russia

00:03:45.68 --> 00:03:46.61
into Ukraine?

00:03:46.61 --> 00:03:51.56
What kind of help might NATO members provide?

00:03:51.56 --> 00:03:56.03
Well, it would depend a lot on the nature of the expansion

00:03:56.03 --> 00:03:58.22
of Russian military in Ukraine.

00:03:58.22 --> 00:04:04.82
Should it be a ground war with tanks rolling across territory,

00:04:04.82 --> 00:04:09.08
aerial strikes, you would see large numbers of refugees that

00:04:09.08 --> 00:04:10.67
would need to be accommodated.

00:04:10.67 --> 00:04:15.50
NATO would have to increase its military support for Ukraine

00:04:15.50 --> 00:04:18.32
to try to claw back territory.

00:04:18.32 --> 00:04:21.38
Hopefully, we don't get to that stage.

00:04:21.38 --> 00:04:26.81
Regardless of the scale of an invasion,

00:04:26.81 --> 00:04:31.58
we would likely see sanctions against Russia

00:04:31.58 --> 00:04:36.08
to try to increase the cost of any further expansion

00:04:36.08 --> 00:04:38.64
of military activity.

00:04:38.64 --> 00:04:41.07
One thing to be concerned about, of course,

00:04:41.07 --> 00:04:45.23
is that NATO countries are also bordering with Ukraine.

00:04:45.23 --> 00:04:48.86
And conflicts like this are often

00:04:48.86 --> 00:04:52.55
difficult to contain as weapons are going back and forth

00:04:52.55 --> 00:04:55.83
and people are going back and forth between countries.

00:04:55.83 --> 00:04:59.06
So one thing that NATO really needs to be concerned about

00:04:59.06 --> 00:05:01.82
is any potential spillover of fighting

00:05:01.82 --> 00:05:06.03
in Ukraine that then crosses border onto a NATO country.

00:05:06.03 --> 00:05:08.64
And that would cause a real political, economic,

00:05:08.64 --> 00:05:10.92
and military crisis.

00:05:10.92 --> 00:05:13.40
So better contain-- better diplomacy,

00:05:13.40 --> 00:05:15.08
not get to any Russian aggression.

00:05:15.08 --> 00:05:18.26
Timothy Frye, thank you so much for joining us tonight.

00:05:18.26 --> 00:05:19.05
It was my pleasure.

00:05:19.05 --> 00:05:20.74
Thank you.